Things about time that nobody should have to know: It is so much more complicated to determine how to format midnight and noon than you'd think.
The US GPO used `12 p.m.` for midnight and `12 m.` for noon until 2000, in which it was `12 p.m.` and `12 a.m.` respectively. It didn't flip to how we use it until 2008.
I think we should bring back `12 m.`, personally.

@everyone,¬†does this make sense regarding meeting cadence?
The callout is spitballing, I just thought about our current newsletter situation.
"each with two clubs meeting simultaneously." like over lapping each other or back to back??
Yeah, that was my only concern. I can imagine it being unfortunate for some if they have to pick and choose their meetings

The original idea was back-to-back 30-minute meetings, perhaps with a buffer in between for run over. So instead of two clubs meeting from 7 to 8 o'clock, with one starting at 7 and the other starting at 7.30, We could do like a window of 7 to 8.30 With like a 30-minute break in between. Or we can just keep the one-hour meetings, but have two on the same night with like a 15-minute break in between or something. This is the reason I wanted to talk about it. I know that everybody kind of silently agreed that four different one-hour meetings (plus the main meeting every week / every other week) was a heck of a lot to try to attend.
I see! That makes more sense. I feel like we pretty regularly fill an hour so I don't know how beneficial it would be to shrink it, but a break between would definitely be ideal
And yet no level ups

Hahaha that's because I've only been running it live for under an hour. Once hosted 24/7 it'll be better XD

I'd prefer back to back rather than overlapping since I don't want to miss out on a meeting for another. 30min would be kind of short so I'd suggest we keep it an hour long (leaves room to elaborate in meetings and have people feel free to discuss and engage) but I would appreciate an intermission before the following meeting.
